{{for|the computer programmer|brian d foy}} {{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | image = Sevenlittlefoys-Jan22-1916.jpg | caption = Bryan Foy performing as part of ''The Seven Little Foys'' in 1916 | name = Bryan Foy | birth_date = {{Birth date|1896|12|8}} | birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], United States | death_date = {{Death date and age|1977|4|20|1896|12|8}} | death_place = Los Angeles, United States | burial_place = [[Calvary Cemetery, East Los Angeles]] | occupation = Film producer, film director | parents = [[Eddie Foy Sr.]] | relatives = [[Eddie Foy Jr.]], brother | years_active = 1923–1963 }} '''Bryan Foy''' (December 8, 1896 &ndash; April 20, 1977) was an American [[film producer]] and [[film director|director]]. He produced 214 films between 1924 and 1963. He also directed 41 films between 1923 and 1934. He headed the [[B picture]] unit at [[Warner Bros.]] where he was known as "the keeper of the B's".<ref>p. 430 Senn, Bryan ''Golden Horrors'' 1996 McFarland</ref>
==Biography== He was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]], on December 8, 1896. He was the eldest son of the vaudeville star [[Eddie Foy, Sr.|Eddie Foy]] and appeared with his father in the [[vaudeville]] act "Eddie Foy and The Seven Little Foys." The act broke up when Bryan Foy left to join the U.S. Army in World War I in 1918,<ref name=Travel>{{cite web |url=https://travsd.wordpress.com/2010/03/09/stars-of-vaudeville-130-eddie-foy-the-seven-little-foys-and-the-youngest-foy-of-all/ |publisher=Travalanche |title=Stars of Vaudeville #130: Eddie Foy, the Seven Little Foys, and the Youngest Foy of All |accessdate=December 29, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6e9RjISoH?url=https://travsd.wordpress.com/2010/03/09/stars-of-vaudeville-130-eddie-foy-the-seven-little-foys-and-the-youngest-foy-of-all/ |archivedate=December 30, 2015 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> after which his remaining siblings continued performing with their father under the title, "Eddie Foy and the Younger Foys", through 1923, when their father retired.<ref name=EFBio>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h4uHH5Kz1DAC&pg=PA243&q=The%20Seven%20Little%20Foys%20vaudeville | title=Eddie Foy: A Biography | last=Fields | first=Armond | pages=243–44 | year=1999 | publisher=McFarland | isbn=0786443286 | accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>
He was also a songwriter, and by 1916 had several published songs, including "My Honolulu Girl".<ref>{{cite news|title=The Aspirations of the Foy Children |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/59620523/?terms=%22Charley%2BFoy%22 |newspaper=The Gazette Globe (Kansas City, Kansas) |date=February 16, 1916 |page=3 |via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = December 31, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>
He produced the [[20th Century Fox]] war movie ''[[Guadalcanal Diary (film)|Guadalcanal Diary]]'' in 1943.
He died in Los Angeles from a heart attack on April 20, 1977. He was buried in [[Calvary Cemetery, East Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Foote|first1=Lisle|title=Buster Keaton's Crew: The Team Behind His Silent Films|date=2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476618067|page=45}}</ref>
