'''John Marsden Beaumont Jones''' (20 December 1920 &ndash; 11 June 1992), known as '''Marsden Jones''', was an emeritus professor and the founder and first director of the Center for Arabic Studies at the [[American University in Cairo]].{{Citation needed|date= October 2011}}

His special interests were early Islam, the early emergence of Islamic institutions, and the study of modern Islamic movements in Egypt. He translated [[Al-Waqidi]]'s ''Kitab al-Tarikh wa al-Maghazi'' and worked on early [[Sirah Rasul Allah|sira]] literature, and he helped publish a series of volumes in Arabic on Leaders of Contemporary Literature in Egypt.{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}}

He was the brother-in-law of [[Philip Jones (civil servant)|Sir Philip Jones]].{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}}

